# Copy this file to .env and fill in values for your project.

# Human-readable project name (used for container name + workdir).
PROJECT_NAME=my-project

# Git repo URL. Use git@ form so the deploy key is used.
REPO_URL=git@github.com:org/repo.git

# Absolute path on THIS machine to the deploy key (private key).
# The key should have commit + pull access to REPO_URL only.
DEPLOY_KEY_PATH=/home/you/.ssh/keys/my-project-deploy

# Port the webapp binds to inside the container.
WEBAPP_PORT=3000

# Optional: shell command to run on every container start, from the repo
# root inside the container. Use this to spin up a dev server, run pending
# migrations, warm caches, etc. If the command blocks (e.g. a foreground
# `pnpm dev`), the container stays alive on it; if it returns, the container
# falls through to a stdin-blocked idle state. To run something in the
# background, append `&` or wrap in `tmux new-session -d -s NAME '...'`.
# A non-zero exit is logged but does not kill the container.
# If the dev server must be reachable from the host, bind to 0.0.0.0 (not
# 127.0.0.1).
# ON_LAUNCH_SCRIPT="pnpm dev"

# Optional: extra ports to publish from the container to the host, beyond
# WEBAPP_PORT. Each entry is either a single port (published as
# host:container on the same number) or "host:container" to remap when the
# host port is busy. All bindings go to 127.0.0.1 only — these are for local
# tools on this machine (DBeaver hitting an in-container ClickHouse, a
# debugger attaching, redis-cli, etc.), not LAN exposure. Whitespace and/or
# newlines separate entries; blanks are ignored.
# EXTRA_PORTS="
# 8123
# 9000
# 16379:6379
# "

# Optional: container resource limits. Defaults: 8g memory, 8 CPUs,
# 16384 pids. Bump PIDS_LIMIT if you plan to run thread-hungry service
# daemons inside (ClickHouse alone asks for 500+ threads at startup).
# MEM_LIMIT=8g
# CPU_LIMIT=8
# PIDS_LIMIT=16384

# Per-project image-tag suffix. The container is created from a tag of the
# shared base image named remote-code-<project>-<suffix>, so VS Code Dev
# Containers keeps each project's attach config separate (a shared image name
# makes it confuse one project's container for another's, even across hosts).
# create-dev-container.sh generates this randomly and writes it here, so the
# same project bootstrapped on two hosts gets two distinct suffixes. If unset
# (e.g. a hand-written .env), it falls back to a 4-char hash of PROJECT_NAME +
# hostname. Set it explicitly only if you want a fixed value.
# IMAGE_SUFFIX=

# Optional: absolute path on the host to a directory of data the container
# should be able to read. Mounted read-only at /root/shared_data inside the
# container. Leave unset to skip the mount.
# SHARED_DATA_PATH=/home/you/data/my-project-inputs

# Optional: expose the webapp (WEBAPP_PORT) to the public internet via a
# Cloudflare quick tunnel. When true, setup.sh starts `cloudflared` in a
# tmux session and prints the public https://*.trycloudflare.com URL in
# the banner. The URL is stable for the container's lifetime and rotates
# on relaunch. No Cloudflare account required.
#
# IMPORTANT — what you're opting into:
#   - The URL is the only access control. Anyone with it can reach the
#     webapp. Treat it like a secret; don't paste in public channels.
#   - Traffic flows through Cloudflare's edge: they terminate TLS and
#     re-encrypt over the tunnel, so they can see request contents.
#   - Any vulnerability in the webapp is now exposed to the open internet
#     instead of just localhost.
#   - Dev frameworks reject requests where Host isn't localhost. You MUST
#     allow the trycloudflare hostname in your dev server config — e.g.
#     for Vite, add `allowedHosts: ['.trycloudflare.com']` to server in
#     vite.config.js (leading dot = wildcard subdomain). Without this
#     you'll get "Blocked request" pages instead of your app.
#   - Enabling this auto-adds api.trycloudflare.com plus a pinned set of
#     Cloudflare argotunnel edge IPs to the egress allowlist (see
#     TUNNEL_EDGE_IPS in launch.sh).
# EXPOSE_WEBAPP=true

# Optional: in addition to the local desktop notification, push an alert
# to your phone via https://ntfy.sh whenever the harness fires a
# notification (task complete / awaiting input). ntfy.sh is a free pubsub
# HTTP service: install the ntfy app on your phone, pick a hard-to-guess
# topic name, and subscribe to it. Anyone who knows the topic can publish
# AND read on it, so treat the topic name like a password.
# ENABLE_NOTIFY_SH_ALERTS=true
# NTFY_SH_TOPIC=your-private-topic-7c4a8b9d

# Optional: two-hop remote setup. Set this on a REMOTE host that runs the
# container(s) but has no desktop of its own (e.g. a KVM/VPS box). Instead of
# rendering, host_notify.sh forwards each event over TCP to host:port -- normally
# a loopback port that an SSH reverse tunnel from your laptop carries back to a
# host_listener.py running there, which renders the popup + sound (notification
# titles are tagged with the container's PROJECT_NAME so you can tell them
# apart). This is HOST-LEVEL: a single listener relays every container on this
# host to one laptop, so set it here in the harness .env, not a per-project one.
# On the laptop, install the always-on services once:
#     ./install_dev_machine_listener.sh <ssh-alias-for-this-host> <PORT>
# (PORT must match below). Leave this UNSET on a laptop running containers
# locally. See docs/Running on a remote host.md.
# RC_FORWARD_ADDR=127.0.0.1:8765

# Optional: IP the container tries to reach at startup to prove the egress
# filter is actually dropping non-allowlisted destinations. Must be
# publicly reachable (so its unreachability is due to OUR filter, not a
# routing dead-end) and must NOT be in your allowlist. Defaults to
# 93.184.216.34 (example.com).
# CANARY_BLOCKED_IP=93.184.216.34

# Optional: how often (seconds) launch.sh re-resolves WHITELIST_HOSTS and
# adds any newly-observed IPs to the live nft set / iptables chain.
# CDN-fronted hosts (archive.ubuntu.com via Cloudflare, github.com, npm,
# etc.) rotate A records, so the launch-time snapshot drifts over long
# sessions — apt/git/pnpm start seeing "Unable to connect" mid-session.
# Add-only: old IPs are kept so in-flight connections aren't broken.
# Default 300 (5 min). Set to 0 to disable the loop.
# RESOLVE_INTERVAL=300

# Hostnames the container is allowed to reach (in addition to the git host,
# which is auto-added). Every outbound connection to any IP not resolved from
# this list is dropped at the host firewall. Keep it tight — only what the
# project, package managers, and claude actually need.
# One per line. Blank lines and extra whitespace are ignored.
#
# Rootless+pasta mode: loopback (127.0.0.0/8) is accepted automatically so
# the container can reach the host's DNS stub (e.g. 127.0.0.53 with
# systemd-resolved). DNS exfiltration via the stub is still possible — see
# TODO.md. Upstream resolvers (1.1.1.1, 8.8.8.8) are NOT allowlisted by
# default; add them here only if you explicitly want them.
WHITELIST_HOSTS="
github.com
objects.githubusercontent.com
codeload.github.com
raw.githubusercontent.com
api.github.com
registry.npmjs.org
pypi.org
files.pythonhosted.org
api.anthropic.com
platform.claude.com
statsig.anthropic.com
sentry.io
mise.jdx.dev
archive.ubuntu.com
security.ubuntu.com
update.code.visualstudio.com
vscode.download.prss.microsoft.com
marketplace.visualstudio.com
"
